<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11136&amp;p=128775#p128775</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11136&amp;p=128775#p128775"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: 4th to 5th generation biggest leap?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11136&amp;p=128775#p128775"><![CDATA[
I'd come to think of the TG16 as &quot;in the middle&quot; because all of the features felt very &quot;natural evolution&quot; of the previous generation...<br />Relative to the NES: 4 times as many palettes, 5 times as many non-transparent colors per palette, 16 times as many directly-enumerable tiles, 4 times the CPU speed, 9 times as many colors in the master palette, three times as many pixel aspect ratios (or dot clocks), obvious linear improvements in sound generator (but still chip-like) and included bankswitching.<br />Relative to the SMS: 8 times as many palettes, 8 times as many directly-enumerable tiles, ≈4-7 times the CPU speed, 8 times as many colors in the master palette, twice as many (and much more versatile) voices in the sound generator (Ignoring the Mark 3's FM synth, since it wasn't released outside Japan).<br /><br />The SNES added features that weren't simply the logical evolution of the previous generation:<br />Relative to the SNES: only one (usually; the SuperGrafx provided two) independent backgrounds instead of 2-4 depending. No affine matrix transformations. No native sample playback (no reverb). 15bpp color is finally large enough that you no longer have to figure out how to work around it (/ are freed from the paralysis of infinite choice). There are a few linear improvements here, too: half as many sprites, twice as many palettes, eight times as many directly-enumerable tiles, one more dotclock...<br /><br />I'm probably missing some things, and I haven't any background to speak on behalf of other contemporary machines.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Wed May 14, 2014 1:54 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
