<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11136&amp;p=127366#p127366"><![CDATA[
True, but the 3D leap was still important because it allowed for a behind-the-character viewpoint. Behind-the-character allows for far longer distances than a side or overhead view. Otherwise, when a character is moving rapidly across the landscape, the player can't react in time to obstacles or items that just scrolled into view. This let games get away from a &quot;world map&quot;, &quot;town map&quot;, and &quot;indoor map&quot; at three separate scales in favor of one seamless map, leading to the whole sandbox genre.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Apr 02, 2014 1:04 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
