<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: 4th to 5th generation biggest leap?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11136&amp;p=127365#p127365"><![CDATA[
I think first to second was the biggest leap because we went from consoles dedicated (largely) to one single game to a cartridge/microprocessor architecture that allowed you to simply change cartridges to get a vastly different game, which is pretty much the foundation that modern consoles are based on, and what made them more like appliances and computers rather than toys. Every other generation is just better video and sound, which is still significant in itself, but nothing really as groundbreaking as &quot;this system can run a hypothetically infinite number of applications that all are unique&quot;.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=21">Drag</a> — Wed Apr 02, 2014 12:00 pm</p><hr />
